<PROGRAM_THEORY name="THICK_DESCRIPTION_AFTER_THE_EVENT">

<PURPOSE>
  Build a theory-machine for the paper.

  The paper asks:

  How does <meaningful_action> survive after <the_event> disappears?

  Answer:

  <thick_description> [converts
] <vanishing_public_action>
  INTO <inscribed_social_discourse>
  BY [reading
] <behavior> AS <symbolic_action>
  THROUGH <public_codes>, <actor_frames>, <power_relations>, and <interpretive_conflicts>.

  The paper’s central claim:

  <culture> is not <behavior>, not <private_mind>, not <total_way_of_life>, not <formal_structure>.
  <culture> is the <public_context_of_significance> within which <action> becomes legible.
</PURPOSE>


<CORE_PROBLEM>
  <event> [happens
]
  <event> [passes
]
  <event> [cannot_be_recovered_as_event
]

  Therefore:

  <ethnographer> [must_inscribe
] <the_said_of_the_event>

  But:

  <inscription> is not <neutral_capture>
  <inscription> is <interpretation_of_interpretations>

  Therefore:

  <anthropological_knowledge> [must_be_appraised
] by its power to:
    - [distinguish
] <wink> FROM <twitch>
    - [distinguish
] <gesture> FROM <motion>
    - [distinguish
] <case> FROM <microcosm>
    - [distinguish
] <trace> FROM <meaning>
    - [distinguish
] <interpretation> FROM <fantasy>
</CORE_PROBLEM>


